title: Prusa i4 X linear Rail support

description.text:
Do to the small lash in the X linear Rail I make a support guide and attached a new Linear Rail on the X axis (270mm) this is so much better now and run like a dream, much better quality in fast print.
I change my new linear rail with one of the z axis, do to the Black color, the new was in steel color. I also heated in some small Brass tread. Watch out, this is not easy, try on an old print tol earn how to do it, or use small bolt insted.

I make a small video of the Work, speed is X8, it`s NOT a" how to do" but a "see how I do it"

NOTE: you can download the file in 3mm and 4mm bed Mount hole. if you want to try heat in the small brass tread use 4mm hole.

Linear Rail 270mm:
http://www.aliexpress.com/item/3d-printer-mgn12-linear-guide-L575mm-1pc-MGN12H-made-in-china/32677296086.html

See the video
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-rPAZKg_Bt8

comments.text: I think that a dual rails system is a good idea. But I have an i4 as well and I saw a lot of slop in mine. Tearing it down I saw that the problem was with the MGN12 carriage itself. I could rock it back on forth a little bit. I ordered a 300 mm replacement from Amazon and when I got the unit in I was going to replace it but I saw that the rails were the same except for the color. So I butted up the new rail to the old one and slid the new carriage onto the black rail. Moved to the back and slid the old carriage onto the rail in my hand. Put everything back together and it now has no slop at all. Works great. Amazon sells a 100 mm rail with a MGN12 for about $10 free shipping, the carriage itself is $12 with free shipping. Aliexpress is cheaper but a much longer wait time (They really need to take the express out of there name). You may want to look into checking or replacing your carriage even if you do this mod or not

description.text:
This part was designed to hold an IR LED from a Trackmate or iLaps transponder. If mounted poorly, the transponders are susceptible to damage, and that usually means the LED gets ripped off.

One solution, is to de-solder the LED and 'Remote' mount it using this p[art and some small gauge silicone wire. Then if it does somehow manage to get hit, it will break the wire and you can easily replace the LED without damaging the transponder itself.

This one is for a 5mm standoff. If different diameters are desired I can create more, just leave a note in the comments.

description.text:
You did not know that you need this. It dips any food in chocolate and sprinkle. Made for showing off at Aarhus Mini Maker Fair (AMMF) Oct. 2016 - It worked. Based on the AUP3Steel wide frame (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1689048) and with different mounts/fixtures for:
A) Holding fruit
B) Holding chocolate and sprinkle
C) Holding cooling fan and serving cups.

With home made program for Gcode generation and sending (Lazarus source code included). 6 years old kids could operate the machine (several have done) and almost 400 fruits was dipped and eaten at the two day AMMF (12 hr in total). So so fun....

Enjoy and have fun

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

RepRapPro

Infill:

40%

Notes:

A lot of milling and drilling is to be done.

Instructions

I am not a programmer and do not clam to be - thus the code is simple and infantile - please feel free to take the ideas and scrap the rest and please feel free not to comment on my poor skills. With that out of the way....

This is an add on to the AUP3steel wide printer frame (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1689048)

The chocolate heating was done by an second Arduino and the code, pads, wiring etc. was performed by Peter (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1834162) - really nice work.

All plates was CNC routed and mounted on electronic stubs - all some I had around the workshop. The chocolate heater was mounted by the very simple clips.

The only tricky part was the toothpick and ejector. STL for this is given and the servo motor was just jammed into the holder. The ejector wire was at first a piece of Cu wire (1,7 Ø) and then welding tread (ASTM 304, 1,4mm Ø) and finally spring steel (1,2 mm Ø). All worked and the final applied was the one of spring steel (by random).

Connection of the servo to Ramps was done inspired by a blog that I have lost the link to (Sorry to you all). In short.
1) Use PSU 5V+ to power you Servos (or the USB and thus the Arduino will shot down). Use a three lagged Dupont plug with power in center. Please - you can damage your electronics here - be sharp and power 5V+ on the middle pin!
2) Plugin your servo (the right way)
3) Enable servos in Marlin: In configuration.h and uncomment the line: #define NUM_SERVOS 3
4) Now you can move your servos with M280 Px Sy where x is servo number and y is angle in degrees.

Please note that Mxxx codes do not buffer as Gxxx codes does. Thus if you would like to have the servo to move sequential with the Gcode - then add M400(empty buffer before requesting a new command) before the code.

title: Bun Twist Hair Accessory
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
I have bought hair accessories similar to this that I like, but were way to big for my hair since I don't have a lot of it. Too thick of plastic, not enough bend, and too long, and the hooks were too small and came apart easily. I took my favorite hair accessory and made it smaller, thinner, and easier to manage for thin hair. I printed a bunch of these, they work much better than the ones I bought.

I recommend warming the plastic well with a hair dryer before twisting hair up in it the first time so it gets a "flex" and shapes itself to your hair.

To use, you take all of your hair and put it through the center. Bring the accessory to the bottom of your hair length with hooks on either end and roll your hair up around the pin. Then pull the ends together and clip together the hooks. Its good for clean perfect buns, or messy buns, but overall a very quick and easy hair style.

description.text:
This is a pinhole camera, ... with the shape of a human eye, i know what you are thinking , ¡¡¿how im gonna put film on that??!!!, well, you can put film roll, but you will need to cut ir in triangle shape to fit them all, and connecnting them with tape on the back
( of course you have to do this in a dark room), or even better, you can just a single strip horizontally or vertically in order to create a panoramic photo with the center on high focus and the sides very blurry.

The idea with this is to recreate the mechanism that our eyes use to capture images, so you have to know that the center is the only part that is going to be focused, because the more the paper is colse to the aperture, the more is going to get blurry, is how our peripheral sight works, is not going to take super professional photos, but is interesting to try it.

The aperture that i reccomend to use in this, is a 3mm diameter hole, wich means: f/50 .

The camera comes with a lid that closes the hole, you just have to slide it through the hole that is in the "cornea"; in order to close the camera correctly and make this effiecient, i strongly suggest to print in black filament and use some screws and screw washers

description.text: Basically a housing for a throwie.  Once glued together it's super easy to drop an LED and CR2032 coin cell inside.
Use a laser cutter to cut the parts.  Glue them together with super glue.  Drop an LED in and a coin cell behind it.  The fit should be tight enough to stay without glue or tape.

Individual Y-rod mounts which attach between the x-axis frame extrusions.  These are designed to address three things about the "original" y-rod mount...  #1 - these allow you to choose whatever rod-spacing you desire.  #2 - these allow 100% maximum travel of your print bed within the limits of your frame (the original y-rod mount could, depending on your table design, interfere with travel by as much as 15mm front and back).  #3 - take advantage of the superiority of the MendelMax extruded frame to absolutely level your y-rods
Listed as "a work in progress".  I have been using for a few weeks now and do not forsee any forthcoming changes...

I am not an OpenSCAD designer so .STL files only are available. All files have been run through NetFabb, verified and printed. With these in place, I have 280mm full printable space in the Y-axis. TWO IMPORTANT NOTES

description.header: 1 - Because these mount between the frame extrusions, they require at least 455mm long y-rods.  (Why not 460?  The "back" mount is press-fit, with a 5mm thick end.)
2 - because of the tight confines inside the mount, it is required to have a "stubby" hex key to tighten the frame mounting screws.  I simply cut an extra one I had down to about 5mm.
description.text:
Print (2X) each piece. I designate the two different mounts as "front" and "back", but implement them as you feel fit... 2 of each... 4 of of either, if you want... These are designed at exactly at 30mm... the designed spacing between the MM's x and y axis frame extrusions. Print accuracy is critical to utilizing these for item #3 - "perfect" rod level. Print / measure / light sand with a solid sanding block to get them all exactly the same size.
Installation on a new build will be a much easier task than changing over to these on an existing machine. Key to getting this all lined up as intended is to completely loosen all mounting screws on your lower vertex pieces so that these "lock" your front and rear x-axis extrusions down tight and setting your y-rods in the same plane, then tightening the screws for your y-axis extrusions to square up the lower "box". Lastly, use some down-force to "seat" the upper half of your MM into alignment and tighten the rest of the screws. (Those of you with an MM will inderstand that a lot better than someone unfamiliar with the MM assembly process, I am sure)
The rest is just careful fine-tuning of the y-rod end spacing to get them perfectly aligned. Hardware required :
(8) M5 x 10 screws
(4) M5 x 12 screws (2 each for the rod clamps... 10mm is just a tad short)
(4) M5 hex nuts (2 each for the rod clamps)
(12) M5 washers

description.text:
Remixed from The O'Cello http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1703629 and https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2672095

This are some add-on extras for the wonderful O'Cello. If you make the O'Cello then you can also add these if you like to improve stability without the tripod.

I have designed a chest-rest, a 4th finger position, and knee braces. I currently have the chest-rest/finger position super-glued to the middle part and that part attached with velcro to the O'Cello. I hope to change this to attach it to the second bolt from the top, but I am working with the O'Cello creator to modify the original parts to accommodate this.

The 370mm offset L aluminum bar is attached with the existing 45mm M5 bolts. The bars I used was Hillman 1/16" x 1/2" x 3/4" - 3feet

You may also notice that I drilled a hole in the last piece so that the center rod could extend all the way to the ground. I then added a clamp with a thumbscrew and put the extra rod part side-by-side -you will have to cut to fit your own playing method.

UPDATE:
I've uploaded a version of the middle part of the chest rest which should fit into the current version of the O'Cello.

UPDATE 2:
I really liked the Scroll'ello for you O'cello, but I didn't want to reprint my O'Cello Part 1 because I made it out of carbon fiber PLA to withstand the string tension, so I made it a cap which you slide over the original Part 1. I got this idea from the Hovalin Neck Topper https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2113171

description.text:
Watch: https://youtu.be/pdFCBuTAVp4

These blinking goggles use a remix of my Print-In-Place Iris Box (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1817180) which is a remix of emmett's Preassembled Iris Box (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1811143). Right and left "eyeballs" snap into the goggles and a 3D printed spring holds them open. A discrete piece of fishing line is used to actuate the blink. Or you can also skip the spring and the fishing line and just reach up and operate each iris manually. Optionally, you can add "lenses" to enhance the look.

Printer Brand:

MakerGear

Printer:

M2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Print one regular eyeball and one mirrored eyeball for the right and left sides. Also print the spring and the goggles themselves. Print the goggles part more slowly and maybe hotter than normal to make sure that the little fingers that grab the eyeballs have fully fused layers.

NOTE: Also see: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1817180 for more tips on how to successfully print the eyeballs.

In addition to the 3D printed parts, you will need about 12" of 3/8" wide (or 10mm) elastic, and about 36" (1m) of fishing line. After printing the eyeballs, you will have to cut way the small tabs that hold the bottom of each iris leaf in place. Then insert a small flat bladed screwdriver between the outer sphere and the studded ring to break away the outer sphere from the base. When everything is freed up, rotating the outer sphere relative to the base ring will open and close the iris. Run the eyeballs open and closed many times until they operated freely. Add a drop of light oil to the leafs so that they operate very smoothly.

The right and the left irises operate in different directions. When mounted in the goggles with the irises open and the little actuator tabs at the top, they should open when the tab is moved to the outside of the goggles. Snap each eyeball in place accordingly. Be very gentle because the little fingers on the goggles can break if overflexed. (You can glue them back in place if one or two break.)

Next, insert the spring into the tabs as shown in the photos. The irises should want to spring open. If they want to close, swap the eyeballs. Tie one end of your fishing line thru the hole in the right side of the spring, thread it down thru the eyelet in the right side of the goggles and back up thru the eyelet in the left side of the goggles. Finally tie it off to the left side of the spring. Lastly, thread your elastic through the slots in the side of the goggles.

Put on the goggles. Loop your thumb through the big loop of fishing line and pull downward to blink. Both sides must be pulled at the same time or else the spring will jam.

Optional Lenses: Cut out two 1.75" diameter discs from tinted acrylic sheet (3mm thick or thinner is ideal). Cut flats on each side so that the distance across the flats is 1.525". Slide each disc into the front opening, center and press up against the iris-side of the inner sphere and carefully super glue into place.

UPDATE: For additional assembly instructions check out NeatherBot's great video posted as part of his iris goggle make: http://www.thingiverse.com/make:263657

description.text:
This is a led ring light I build specifically for my Panasonic HDC-SD 909.
It is a ring of bright leds which surround the camera lens. The inner diameter of it is 7cm the outer diameter is 12cm. The distance to the camera mount is 6 cm. If your camera more or less fits those numbers (+-0,5 cm) you can print it as it is. Otherwise it is easily adjustable. It comes with a build in battery housing, designed by Obijuan. 48 leds are needed.

You need to get at least 48 led. In my case I used leds with 3V each. Print out both parts. First take the led ring and put in the leds. Then solder pairs of leds (2 leds in a row) together. Then solder all led pairs parallel to each other (take a look at the picture to see how I have connected them. Then connect them to 4 batteries (AAA or AA) which need to be connected in a row. This makes 2 leds 3V = 4 batteries 1,5V. If you are not sure about the connections order some more leds and play around a bit. Finally screw the two parts together with a small screw, using the printed hole at the connection. Mount your Camera and have fun! description.text:
If you like my work please consider buying me a coffee!

This is a complete amplifier based on a PAM8403 chip or similar.

I used common electronic pieces that you can get very cheap in china (3,50€ total per unit for me including printing) and designed around it for a wide variety of components.

The PAM8403 isn't especially loud but i have many uses for a small amplifier like that. (Kitchen/bathroom radio..)

You can completely alterate the design via the fusion360 archive file to suit your components or remove the texts.

Wenn euch meine Arbeit gefällt könnt ihr mir gerne einen Kaffee ausgeben!

Schreibt mir, wenn ihr eins meiner Things ausgedruckt haben wollt.

Dies ist ein kompletter Verstärker basierend auf dem PAM8403 Chip.

Das Design basiert auf geläufigen Bauteilen die man günstig aus China bekommt. (Inklusive Druck lande ich bei 3,51€ pro Einheit, günstiger ist möglich.)

Der PAM Chip ist nicht besonders laut aber ich habe ihn schon öfter in einfacheren Anwendungen benutzt. (Küchenradio, Duschbeschallung etc.)

Über die Fusion360 Archiv Datei könnt ihr alle Maße ändern wenn ihr andere Bauteile benutzen wollt.
